%U A393442 68,71,73,74,74,74,56,64,71,77,82,86,89,91,92,92,92,67,76,84,91,97,102,106,109,111,112,112,112,79,89,98,106,113,119,124,128,131,133,134,134,134
%N A393442 Array read by downward antidiagonals: T(n,k) (n>=0, k>=0) is the maximum number of regions the plane can be divided into by drawing n circles and k lines.
%C A393442 The individual circles can have any radii; the lines are infinite.
%D A393442 David O. H. Cutler, Jonas Karlsson, and Neil J. A. Sloane, Cutting a Pancake with an Exotic Knife, In preparation, March 25 2026.
%D A393442 Jacob Steiner, Einige Gesetze über die Theilung der Ebene und des Raumes, J. Reine Angew. Math., 1 (1826), 349-364. See Eq. (23). [Note that the title uses the old spelling of Teilung. This is not a typo.]  Note also that the formula in (23) is wrong if there are no lines, in that case (11) must be used.
%H A393442 Paolo Xausa, <a href="/A393442/b393442.txt">Table of n, a(n) for n = 0..11324</a> (first 150 antidiagonals, flattened).
%F A393442 T(n,k) = 1+k+2*n*k+k*(k-1)/2+n*(n-1), except T(n,0) = n^2-n+2 if n >= 1.
%e A393442 The array begins:
